  "findings": {
    "wasted_verify_eliminated": "p-min removes wasted multi-row verifies (drafted >=1, accepted 0): wasted0 3->1->0 (B=1), 4->1->0 (B=2), 3->1->0 (B=3) as p_min 0->0.5->0.65. The MTP head's depth-1 confidence predicts zero-accept cycles -- it knows when it is unsure (bimodal accept hist confirmed).",
    "pmin05_sweet_spot": "p_min=0.5 is the sweet spot for B>=2: avg_accept UNCHANGED (B=2 1.214, B=3 1.583) while estimated launches/visible-token drop ~9-12% (B=3 647->575, B=2 646->589). It converts wasted verifies to cheap AR WITHOUT sacrificing real accepts -- a dispatch-floor reduction that STACKS with #101/#105.",
    "pmin065_over_truncates": "p_min=0.65 (on the proxy) cuts cycles that WOULD accept: avg_accept B=2 1.214->1.067, B=3 1.583->1.214; launches/token stop improving. Too aggressive on this head.",
    "b1_no_benefit": "B=1 has no multi-row waste (1 draft = 2 rows); p-min only turns accept-1 cycles into AR, monotonically lowering avg_accept 0.824->0.722->0.600 and raising launches/token 653->677. p-min is pure loss at B=1.",
    "vs_stepfun": "Confirms StepFun's p-min insight (p-min reduces wasted dispatch on rejects), but our optimum is B=3 + p_min=0.5 (575 launches/visible-token), NOT B=1. Reason: our verify has a high FIXED launch cost (711, #98) that amortizes better over higher B; StepFun's B=1 optimum on MI50 reflects llama.cpp's different cost structure + a separate small draft model. p-min generalizes; the B-optimum is stack-specific.",
    "launch_headroom": "All spec configs sit at 575-677 estimated launches/visible-token vs plain AR's 920 (#98) -- the #98 launch model says MTP spec already undercuts AR per visible token. Realizing it as wall tok/s needs the #101/#105 dispatch work (the reload_d2h proposer wall is non-representative)."
  },
